<!-- Installs VMware Tools during the specialize pass, from the CD-ROM
     ESXi itself mounts there (esxi.py's create_vm calls
     vm.MountToolsInstaller() right after the VM is created, before
     power-on, so it's already present by the time Setup gets here - no
     unit number to track, ESXi manages that device itself). This is what
     makes a DHCP deployment's guest IP discoverable at all without a
     human logging in at the console: without VMware Tools running,
     HypervisorDriver.get_guest_ip() has nothing to report (confirmed the
     hard way - a real deployment spun for a full
     WINRM_REACHABILITY_MAX_ATTEMPTS on exactly this gap). A static
     deployment doesn't strictly need this for IP discovery (its address
     is already known declaratively), but gets Tools installed anyway -
     useful for the console mouse (already covered by the USB xHCI
     controller during Setup itself, but VMware Tools also runs signed
     Windows Update-delivered driver updates and improves overall
     guest/host integration), and it means the guest-reported IP can
     cross-check the declared static one after the fact if that's ever
     useful.

     Deliberately does NOT rely on WillReboot=OnRequest's return-code
     contract (0/1/2, anything else fails the whole installation
     outright per that element's own documented behavior) even though
     that's the more "correct" mechanism for a command that conditionally
     needs a reboot: mapping setup64.exe's own exit code (which itself
     already overloads 0/3010/other meanings) into that specific 0/1/2
     contract correctly, in batch syntax, without a real test cycle to
     verify against, was judged riskier than the two-command split below.
     Instead: this command's exit code is unconditionally forced to 0
     (`& exit /b 0` at the end, regardless of whether setup64.exe
     succeeded, failed, or was never found - matching every other
     "never worth failing the whole deployment over this" best-effort
     step elsewhere in this pipeline), and a second, trivial,
     always-succeeding command right after does nothing but trigger the
     actual reboot via WillReboot=Always - simple, unconditional, exactly
     what that value's own documentation describes, no return-code
     mapping to get wrong. Confirmed via Microsoft's own docs that Setup
     resumes any remaining RunSynchronousCommand entries after a
     WillReboot-triggered restart, so anything after this pair (there is
     nothing else right now) would still run.

     REBOOT=ReallySuppress on the installer itself, not left to its own
     default behavior: a documented VMware Tools/VMXNET3 interaction
     causes an immediate network disconnect ("RPC service unavailable")
     if the installer's own driver update takes effect without a full
     restart - exactly why the second command's controlled reboot right
     after exists at all, rather than leaving this to a human or a much
     later reboot elsewhere in the pipeline.

     cmd.exe's own if/else-if chain, not a FOR loop: avoids the
     %/%%-escaping ambiguity between inline cmd.exe invocation and .bat
     file execution entirely, at the cost of checking each candidate
     drive letter explicitly (D/E/F, matching where a second CD-ROM
     mounted after the Windows install media's own D: would be expected
     to land) rather than scanning generically. -->
<RunSynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
    <Description>Install VMware Tools if present (best-effort)</Description>
    <Order>{{ 4 if template.custom_admin_enabled else 3 }}</Order>
    <Path>cmd.exe /c if exist D:\setup64.exe (start /wait "" D:\setup64.exe /S /v"/qn REBOOT=ReallySuppress") else if exist E:\setup64.exe (start /wait "" E:\setup64.exe /S /v"/qn REBOOT=ReallySuppress") else if exist F:\setup64.exe (start /wait "" F:\setup64.exe /S /v"/qn REBOOT=ReallySuppress") &amp; exit /b 0</Path>
</RunSynchronousCommand>
<RunSynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
    <Description>Controlled reboot so a VMware Tools network driver update (if one was just installed) takes effect cleanly instead of disconnecting the network live</Description>
    <Order>{{ 5 if template.custom_admin_enabled else 4 }}</Order>
    <Path>cmd.exe /c exit /b 0</Path>
    <WillReboot>Always</WillReboot>
</RunSynchronousCommand>
